vectorData.altText: 7. What is the name for the connective tissue structures of the thymus, as indicated by the letter A, that divides its parenchyma into lobules?
That's right!  Septae or trabeculae of the capsule are CT structures that divide the parenchyma of thymus into lobules.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

The thymus is a nodular organ posterior to the sternum in the anterior mediastinum. It is largest and most active in youth and decreases in size and activity with age.
At the gross level, it consists of irregular left and right lobes surrounded by a CT capsule. Septae or trabeculae of the capsule divide the parenchyma into lobules.
Vessels, nerves and efferent lymphatics run in the capsule and septae to reach the parenchyma.
The thymus has no afferent lymphatics and is not involved in initiating immune responses.
Each lobule has a cortex and a medulla. The cortex is darker-staining, with numerous small lymphocytes (thymocytes), epithelioreticular cells and macrophages. The medulla is lighter-staining with fewer lymphocytes, but also with epithelioreticular cells. 
Nascent T-cells from the bone marrow enter the cortex and develop immunocompetence by expressing antigen-specific T cell receptors (TCR) on their cell membranes.
